<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="5"><b>Locked out by the "Wal-Mart of garbage"</b></font><p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">July 20, 2007 | Page 16</font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>TODD CHRETIEN reports on a showdown pitting workers in the East Bay against the corporate giant Waste Management.</b><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">FIVE HUNDRED scabs are collecting trash in Oakland, Calif., and other East Bay cities after Waste Management (WM) locked out 481 drivers from Teamsters Local 70 on July 2.<p>
Despite threats of being fired, the rest of WM's local union workforce--including 80 members of the International Association of Machinists (IAM) Local 1546 and more than 300 members of the International Longshore and Warehouse Union (ILWU) Local 6--honored Teamster picket lines.<p>
As the lockout stretched into a third week in mid-July, the unions extended their pickets to other nearby WM facilities in an appeal for solidarity, and a Teamsters picket line at the Port of Oakland caused a several-hours-long work stoppage by ILWU on July 16.<p>
With more action in the offing as <i>Socialist Worker </i>went to press, the fight against WM is becoming an important showdown for the Bay Area labor movement as a whole.<p>
"Waste Management wants slaves working for them, and they want the rest of the country to bow down to them," said Bob Kuykenball, who has worked for WM for seven years and been a Local 70 member for 35 years.<p>

